Hi

I'm working on an ASP Core 2.0 project that contains in the same controller both API actions returning JSON and actions returning views for simplicity.

I implemented the dual auth considering the following blog :

https://wildermuth.com/2017/08/19/Two-AuthorizationSchemes-in-ASP-NET-Core-2

It works, but because of my mixing API/actions for views in the same controller, If I have such a controller :

`[Authorize]
public class AccountController : Controller
{

//This action only requires coockie auth (OK)
public IActionResult Index()
{
    return View();
}

[Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)]
// This action currently requires BOTH cookie auth AND JWT auth ! (KO)
// Here I would like only JWT, not a cumulative auth 
[Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = JwtBearerDefaults.Aut
public IActionResult Get()
{
return Ok(new[] { "One", "Two", "Three" });
}

}`

and in startup.cs (ConfigureServices)
`// Enable Dual Authentication 
services.AddAuthentication()
.AddCookie(cfg => cfg.SlidingExpiration = true)
.AddJwtBearer(cfg =>
{
cfg.RequireHttpsMetadata = false;
cfg.SaveToken = true;

cfg.TokenValidationParameters = new TokenValidationParameters()
{
ValidIssuer = Configuration["Tokens:Issuer"],
ValidAudience = Configuration["Tokens:Audience"],
IssuerSigningKey = new SymmetricSecurityKey(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(Configuration["Tokens:Key"]))
};

});`

I managed to make it work separately if I don't use the Authorize globally on the Controller, but on each Action instead :

`
public class AccountController : Controller
{

[Authorize]
//This action only requires coockie auth (OK)
public IActionResult Index()
{
    return View();
}

[Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)]
// This action requires now only JWT auth  (OK)
[Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = JwtBearerDefaults.Aut
public IActionResult Get()
{
return Ok(new[] { "One", "Two", "Three" });
}

}`

But I would like to find a way to keep my [Authorize] globally and specify for each needed API actions the JWT bearer auth [Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = JwtBearerDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)] and only it.

Is there a way to do this ?

Is it possible (or can it become possible) to decorate a property on a Controller with the `TempDataAttribute` and read that from the view?  Currently, the following example does not work from my testing.  Setting via `TempData["ErrorMessage"]` does work as expected

**Controller (abbrev)**
```
public class AccountController : Controller
{
    [TempData]
    public string ErrorMessage { get; set; }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Login(LoginViewModel model)
    {
        // DO some  login stuff

        ErrorMessage = "Sorry, your login failed.";
        return View(model);
    }
}
```

**View**
```
@if (TempData.Peek("ErrorMessage") != null)
{
     <div class="alert alert-danger">@TempData["ErrorMessage"]</div>
}
```

